    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-09-17T01:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-09-17T01:30:00-05:00" n="316"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">845.00/9–1748: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in India</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Donovan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-09-17T12:00:00+05:30"
                            >September 17, 1948—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>848. In conversation with Bajpai today he read me letter from Liaquat Ali Khan to
                        <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> re intervention in Hyderabad; Ali Khan
                    stressed danger communal disturbances India Pakistan and Srubal areas and said
                    considerable feeling had been aroused in Pakistan by <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss> entry Hyderabad. Bajpai read to me <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss> reply this note which was conciliatory in tone. It said there
                    had been no communal trouble in India and that <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                        >GOI</gloss> had taken every precaution prevent such outbreaks. It also said
                        <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> entry Hyderabad had been prompted by
                        <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> desire stop deterioration communal
                    situation in India created by Razakars raids.</p>
                <p>Bajpai was very critical Bevin’s statement in Parliament that “warlike
                        spirit”<note n="1" xml:id="d316fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Parliamentary Debates</hi>, House of Commons, 5th series,
                        vol. 456, col. 90.</note> had developed in India. Bajpai said “we have sent
                    him a snorter in reply.” He then remarked “how do they expect us to stay in
                    Commonwealth after such a remark.”</p>
                <p>Sent Department 848; repeated Karachi 156. Department pass London from Delhi.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Donovan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
